For #626 and #677. This makes googletest available for use if you add the `testing` module in your project config file - i.e., `includeModule('testing')`. It defines `TORQUE_TESTS_ENABLED`, with which you should wrap all of your unit tests. It also defines two convenience macros. While before, tests with fixtures would look like this:

``` c++
class VectorFixture : public ::testing::Test
{
   protected: Vector<S32> v, u;
};

TEST_F(VectorFixture, Length)
{
   EXPECT_EQ(v.length(), u.length());
}
```

They can now look like:

``` c++
FIXTURE(Vector)
{
   protected: Vector<S32> v, u;
};

TEST_FIX(Vector, Length)
{
   EXPECT_EQ(v.length(), u.length());
}
```

So we can use actual class names in test names, which I think makes for clearer code with less noise and repetition (i.e. no more `TEST(ClassTest`).

Note: currently tests will fail due to a 'memory leak' caused by `Con::printf` as noted [here](http://www.garagegames.com/community/forums/viewthread/136563/1#comment-858975). The solution is to set `$Con::LogBufferEnabled` to `false` before running tests. This means you won't be able to see the output in the console window in-engine, and will have to check the results in `console.log` after closing the engine.

If you have a function which calls a function on a non-existent object such as follows:

```
function foo()
{
    %firstThing = "chocolate";
    %something = "fudge";
    %somethingElse = %object.mix(%firstThing);
    echo("Mixed " @ %somethingElse);
}
```

And you run said function, i.e.

```
foo();
```

The following will be printed:

```
<input> (0): Unable to find object: '' attempting to call function 'mix'
Mixed fudge
```

What should be printed is "", since returning a previous value from the stack makes little sense.

Hey guys, as I've been struggling with these shader issues for a while, I thought it would be approppriate to post that I've found that the motionBlurFx might suffer from the same issue as my shader.

In the pixel shader it has the following code:

``` hlsl
   // Create the screen position
   float4 screenPos = float4(IN.uv0.x*2-1, IN.uv0.y*2-1, depth*2-1, 1);

   // Calculate the world position
   float4 D = mul(screenPos, matWorldToScreen);
   float4 worldPos = D / D.w;
```

Which I believe to be incorrect for some reason.. If you output the worldPos as the pixelcolor you get something like this:
![Wrong1](http://imagizer.imageshack.us/a/img853/2487/3928.png)

If you move the screen up a bit you get this:
![Wrong2](http://imagizer.imageshack.us/a/img842/9147/fzio.png)

Notice how the position of the sky isn't constant, that should be a hint that something is wrong.

This is what I'd expect it to look like:
